   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1813_11_12_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1813-11-12"/>November 13, 1813<lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute> Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">Madam</persName>,<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p> Last monday I received <add>quite safely</add> the<lb/>
                    box containing my satin<lb/>
                    gown - which I think is a<lb/>
                    beautiful color and I am<lb/>
                    much obliged to you for<lb/>
                    chusing it and for all the<lb/>
                    trouble you took in procuring<lb/>
                    and sending my various<lb/>
                    things which were all exactly<lb/>
                    What I wished -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I have had the enclosed<lb/>
                    draft ready for you since<lb/>
                    the moment I rec<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. the box -<lb/>
                    but I kept it for a few days<lb/>
                    because I thought I should<lb/>
                    have to answer a letter of<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX2">
                  <hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Miles's</persName> Which I do by this<lb/>
                    frank -<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1813_11_12_page02.jpg"/>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName> will I believe in a<lb/>
                    few days send us a pamph<lb/>
                    let under a government<lb/>
                    frank - M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth would<lb/>
                    be much obliged to you if you<lb/>
                    would buy for her six yards<lb/>
                    of trimming for her pelisse<lb/>
                    - she sends a pattern of the<lb/>
                    pelisse &amp; I have tacked to it<lb/>
                    a bit of the <hi rend="underline">sort</hi> of trimming <add>
                  <hi rend="underline">not the color</hi>
               </add>
               <lb/>
                    she would like - She is not <choice>
                  <orig>par<lb/>
                    ticular</orig>
                  <reg>particular</reg>
               </choice> however about having<lb/>
                    it exactly the same - - any <hi rend="underline">solid</hi>
               <lb/>
                    trimming that would not catch<lb/>
                    ravel or <hi rend="underline">fuzz</hi> she would like<lb/>
                    &amp; begs to leave it to your taste<lb/>
                    You can send it between the<lb/>
                    leaves of the pamphlet Perhaps<lb/>
                    you could also send me 6 yards of ribbon same as<lb/>
                    the pattern which you bought at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EyleX1">Eyles's</persName>
               <lb/>
                    Tell me whether you have any<lb/>
                    friend who ever attends India sales<lb/>
                    for we have a great <hi rend="underline">hankering</hi>
               <lb/>
                    after real India muslin<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer> 
                    Truly yours<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1813_11_12_page03.jpg"/>
               <p>List of bills paid by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName>
                  <lb/>
                        for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Miss Edgeworth</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <unclear>To</unclear>Coopers rec<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. for<lb/>
                        8 1/4 y<hi rend="superscript">ds</hi>. dove satin 4..2..6<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EyleX1">Eyles's</persName> - laceman - -8..9..7'2<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FarrX1">Miss Farrel</persName> - 4..6..0<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeadX1">Beadnell</persName> - 10 y<hi rend="superscript">ds</hi>. muslin - 2..5..0<lb/>
                    £19..3..1 1/2<lb/>
                  <unclear>C<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</unclear>
                        By draft of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Miss Honora
                        Edgeworth</persName> on Hoare<lb/>
                        dated Nov. 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1813 - £19..3..1/2<lb/>
                        D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  <lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
